doc.ContractDescription: GAS-PRESSURIZED SPACE SUITS CAUSE INJURIES TO ASTRONAUTS BOTH DURING TRAINING AND ACTUAL EVAS AND SIGNIFICANTLY INCREASE METABOLIC EXPENDITURE. CURRENT ASTRONAUT INJURY PROTECTION SYSTEMS ARE INADEQUATE BECAUSE THEY ARE 1) NOT EASILY CUSTOMIZABLE OR ADJUSTABLE, AND 2) HAVE NOT PREVENTED INJURY THUS FAR. AS WE UTILIZE VARIOUS NEW EXPLORATION AND TRAINING ENVIRONMENTS, WE WILL LIKELY SEE NEW TYPES OF INJURIES ACCRUING TO ASTRONAUTS UNLESS IMPROVED PROTECTION SYSTEMS ARE CREATED. IN OUR PREVIOUS WORK WE HAVE EVALUATED ASTRONAUT INJURY AND DEVELOPED PROTOTYPE PROTECTIVE DEVICES TO IMPROVE COMFORT AND SUIT FIT. WE QUANTIFIED PRESSURE OVER THE UPPER ARM AS A PERSON MOVES INSIDE THE SPACE SUIT, AND REVEALED BODY-SUIT CONTACT AND SUIT ARTICULATION. WE HAVE IDENTIFIED THE MOST RELEVANT FACTORS ATTRIBUTED TO SHOULDER INJURY, INCLUDING ANTHROPOMETRIC DIMENSIONS, INDICATING INDIVIDUAL SUIT FIT IS CRITICAL TO PREVENTING INJURIES. OUR METHODS MEASURE PERFORMANCE FROM A DETAILED LOOK INSIDE THE SUIT (I.E., THE PERSPECTIVE OF THE ASTRONAUT), RATHER THAN ONLY ANALYZING SUIT MOTION EXTERNALLY. THE PRODUCT OF OUR RESEARCH WILL BE TO DEVELOP AN ADJUSTABLE PROTECTION GARMENT TO IMPROVE ASTRONAUT COMFORT AND DECREASE INJURY. TO ENSURE THE GARMENT'S PERFORMANCE, WE WILL DEVELOP AN INJURY MONITORING SYSTEM TO MEASURE HUMAN-SUIT CONTACT AND KINEMATICS OVER THE ENTIRE BODY. THESE SYSTEMS WILL BE TESTED IN REALISTIC EVA ENVIRONMENTS (I.E., IN THE NEUTRAL BUOYANCY LAB, ON THE ARGOS FACILITY, AND/OR IN PLANETARY EXPLORATION MOBILITY TASKS) TO ASSESS ASTRONAUT INJURY AND DISCOMFORT. WE WILL QUANTIFY PRESSURE 'HOT SPOTS', ASSESS COMFORT, AND REDUCE INJURY POTENTIAL DURING EVA TASKS WITH AND WITHOUT THE PROTECTION GARMENT TO ENSURE THAT THE PROPOSED WEARABLE GARMENT DOES NOT CAUSE A PERFORMANCE DECREMENT. LEVERAGING OUR PREVIOUS RESEARCH ON INJURY ANALYSIS, MUSCULOSKELETAL MODELING OF EVA INJURIES, COUNTERMEASURE SYSTEMS DESIGN AND PROTOTYPING, WE WILL DEVELOP SECOND GENERATION COMFORT AND PROTECTION DESIGN CONCEPTS AND A SUIT-CONTACT SENSING SYSTEM.

doc.ContractDescription: COASTAL UPWELLING IS AN IMPORTANT FACTOR IN AIR-SEA HEAT EXCHANGE IN COASTAL AREAS, COASTAL WEATHER AND CLIMATE, AND COASTAL ECOSYSTEM AND FISHERY HEALTH. FUTURE ATMOSPHERIC CLIMATE CHANGE, THROUGH A SHIFT IN ATMOSPHERIC CIRCULATION AND WIND STRESS, MAY AFFECT COASTAL OCEAN UPWELLING DYNAMICS, BUT THE PREDICTED OCEANIC RESPONSE IS STILL NOT WELL CONSTRAINED. THUS, THERE IS A PRESSING NEED TO IMPROVE OUR UNDERSTANDING AND PREDICTIVE SKILL OF COASTAL OCEANIC UPWELLING VARIABILITY AND HOW IT MAY CHANGE IN THE FUTURE. WE PROPOSE TO STUDY THE POTENTIAL FOR CHANGES IN COASTAL UPWELLING IN RESPONSE TO CLIMATE CHANGE. THE PROPOSED STUDY IS DIVIDED INTO THREE PARTS: FIRST, MAKING USE OF EXISTING SATELLITE DATASETS TO IMPROVE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE PHYSICAL CONNECTION BETWEEN MODERN CLIMATE OR ATMOSPHERIC VARIABILITY AND UPWELLING VARIABILITY ON INTERANNUAL TIME SCALES; SECOND, A PROCESS MODEL STUDY OF THE POTENTIAL FOR ABRUPT SHIFTS IN UPWELLING DUE TO GRADUALLY CHANGING FORCING; AND THIRD, A PREDICTION OF COASTAL UPWELLING IN A FUTURE WARM CLIMATE, OBTAINED BY FORCING A HIGH-RESOLUTION REGIONAL COASTAL OCEAN MODEL WITH COUPLED CLIMATE MODEL OUTPUT GENERATED FROM FUTURE CLIMATE CHANGE SCENARIOS OF THE COUPLED MODEL INTERCOMPARISON PROJECT PHASE 5 (CMIP5). THE PROPOSED STUDY WILL USE A RANGE OF SATELLITE PRODUCTS, INCLUDING BASIN-SCALE AND COASTAL SCATTEROMETER WIND PRODUCTS, SEA SURFACE TEMPERATURE, AND SEA SURFACE HEIGHT. THESE WILL FIRST BE USED FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF A NEW PREDICTIVE UPWELLING INDEX AND FOR A STATISTICAL ANALYSIS OF THE RELATION BETWEEN ENSO AND COASTAL UPWELLING. THEN THE SATELLITE PRODUCTS WILL BE USED TO FORCE A HIGHRESOLUTION OCEAN MODEL OF THE U.S.~WEST COAST UPWELLING ZONE. ONCE THE MODEL PREDICTIONS OF UPWELLING RESPONSE TO CLIMATE VARIABILITY ARE TESTED USING THIS APPROACH, THE MODEL WILL BE DRIVEN WITH CMIP5 MODEL OUTPUT TO MAKE FUTURE PREDICTIONS. THE PROPOSED WORK HAS RELEVANCE TO OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE RESPONSE OF UPWELLING TO CLIMATE FORCING ON A RANGE OF TIME SCALES, FROM INTERANNUAL (ENSO-RELATED RESEARCH COMPONENT), TO FUTURE CLIMATE PREDICTIONS. IT MAY ALSO OFFER SOME INSIGHT INTO THE PROXY OBSERVATION OF THE WARMING OF UPWELLING SITES DURING PAST WARM CLIMATES. THUS THE PROJECT IS EXPECTED TO ENHANCE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE DYNAMICS OF THE RESPONSE OF UPWELLING SYSTEMS TO CLIMATE CHANGE. IN ADDITION TO THIS SCIENTIFIC VALUE, THE PROPOSED WORK ADDRESSES A SUBJECT OF BROAD PRACTICAL IMPORTANCE, DUE TO THE ROLE OF UPWELLING IN SUPPORTING ECOSYSTEMS AND FISHERIES. FINALLY, THE WORK WILL FORM THE CORE OF A POSTDOCTORAL PROJECT AND THEREFORE SERVE AS A CRUCIAL DEVELOPMENTAL STEP IN THE CAREER OF AN EARLY-STAGE RESEARCHER.
